using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Text;
using SkiaSharp;

static string DrawSVG()
{
    var stream = new MemoryStream();
    var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(
        new SKRect(0, 0, 500, 500),
        stream);
    using var paint = new SKPaint();
    paint.Color = SKColors.Red;
    canvas.DrawRect(new SKRect(0, 0, 100, 100), paint);
    throw new InvalidOperationException("Simulated drawing error in DrawSomeStuff");
    return Encoding.Default.GetString(stream.ToArray());
}

Console.WriteLine("=== Issue #3259 Reproduction ===");
try
{
    var svg = DrawSVG();
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Caught: {ex.Message}");
}

for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++)
{
    GC.Collect(2, GCCollectionMode.Forced, blocking: true);
    GC.WaitForPendingFinalizers();
    Thread.Sleep(200);
}

for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
{
    var tempStream = new MemoryStream();
    var tempCanvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(new SKRect(0, 0, 100, 100), tempStream);
    using var tempPaint = new SKPaint();
    tempPaint.Color = SKColors.Blue;
    tempCanvas.DrawRect(new SKRect(0, 0, 50, 50), tempPaint);
    GC.Collect(2, GCCollectionMode.Forced, blocking: true);
    GC.WaitForPendingFinalizers();
    Thread.Sleep(100);
}

for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++)
{
    GC.Collect(2, GCCollectionMode.Forced, blocking: true);
    GC.WaitForPendingFinalizers();
    Thread.Sleep(500);
}

Console.WriteLine("SUCCESS: test completed without crash");

proposedResponse.body:
Thanks for the report! We were able to reproduce this issue.

The crash occurs because when `DrawSomeStuff` throws an exception, execution jumps to the outer `catch` block without calling `canvas.Dispose()`. This leaves the native SVG canvas alive, but the managed `SKManagedWStream` becomes eligible for garbage collection (it's held by a `WeakReference` internally). When the GC finalizer runs, the native canvas tries to flush/write through the stream callback, but the managed stream is gone — causing `NullReferenceException` in `SKManagedWStreamWriteProxyImplementation`.

**Tested versions:**
| Version | Result |
|---------|--------|
| 3.116.0 (reported) | ❌ Reproduced |
| 3.119.2 (latest) | ❌ Reproduced |
| main (source) | ❌ Reproduced |

**Workaround:** Wrap the canvas in a `using` statement so it's always disposed, even when an exception occurs:

```csharp
public string DrawSVG()
{
    var stream = new MemoryStream();
    using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(
        new SKRect(0, 0, width, height),
        stream))
    {
        DrawSomeStuff(canvas);
    }
    return Encoding.Default.GetString(stream.ToArray());
}
```

The `using` block ensures the canvas and its owned stream are properly disposed even if `DrawSomeStuff` throws. It also ensures the closing `</svg>` tag is written before you read the stream.

That said, the delegate proxy should handle this gracefully rather than crashing the process — we'll look into adding null-checks to the managed stream callbacks.
